{"key":"processedPost-20292402","value":{"id":20292402,"first":20291687,"last":20643574,"when":1405723368,"utime":"07/19/14 01:42 AM","content":"Any time a coir substrate contaminates on first flush, it was the spawn.&nbsp; You can use coir unpasteurized, although 'cooking' it helps the mycelium get going.<br />Thus, it' not your dirty fingernails or other issues, but dirty grain spawn.&nbsp; I've made my views on shumvbox known, but of course others disagree.&nbsp; Another possibility is you're using lime from a dolomite source.&nbsp; If so, it probably has Mg over 2% to 3%, which can impede mushroom mycelium, giving mold a break.<br />Gypsum helps to alleviate pH swings, but it's not really a buffer.&nbsp; Besides, mushroom mycelium prefers a somewhat acidic substrate.&nbsp; Gypsum mostly helps supply calcium and sulfur, both essential to robust fruit development.<br />RR","title":"Re: Cannot, for the life of me, figure out my contamination source."}}